result.execSummary:
The defendant Latasha Warneice Carter was found guilty of the following charge(s) in this case.

  • Attempt Attempt Robbery with Threat of Force, a class E felony, Wisconsin Statutes 943.32(1)(b).

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

Defendant Latasha Warneice Carter in court with attorney Richard Jeffrey Carpenter.  Defendant Latasha Warneice Carter in custody.  Michael Jerome Lonski appeared for the State of Wisconsin.    

COURT SENTENCED Defendant to a MAXIMUM TERM OF IMPRISONMENT of 39 MONTHS, with credit for 46 days time served; the INITIAL TERM OF CONFINEMENT in the Wisconsin State Prison System is 15 MONTHS; the MAXIMUM TERM OF EXTENDED SUPERVISION is 24 MONTHS. 

The defendant IS eligible for the Challenge Incarceration Program AND the Wisconsin Substance Abuse Programs ONLY AFTER serving the 1st 6 months of the Initial Confinement.

COURT ORDERED THE FOLLOWING CONDITIONS AS TO THE EXTENDED SUPERVISION:
*  No new law violations reaching the level of a probable cause finding.
*  Cooperate with agent.
*  Pay costs, surcharges, assessments, supervision, DNA fees out of bail on deposit, if any; and up to 25% of prison funds with the balance due prior to the end of the Extended Supervision. Failure to pay shall result in a Civil Judgment with tax intercept.
*  Maintain full time / part time employment and or schooling.
*  ABSOLUTE SOBRIETY.
*  AODA assessment and follow up care and treatment./
*  Random urine screens with no positive results. No association with drug users, drug dealers, drug houses, or drug dealings.
*  Mental Health assessment with follow up care and treatment.
*  Take all prescribed medications.
*  Restitution set at ZERO.
*  Defendant required to provide a biological specimen (DNA) to the State Crime Lab for testing.
*  As a convicted felon Defendant shall NEVER be in possession of any firearms or weapons at any time in the future.
*  Defendant can't vote in any election until civil rights are restored.
*  Participate in a Cognitive Thinking Program, and any other programming deemed appropriate by the Department and or agent.
